  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a criminal offense under the legislation of most countries. It is typically addressed in criminal codes or specialized anti-money laundering (AML) laws. Money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear legal. Many countries have specific laws and penalties for money laundering, including:\n\n1. Criminal prosecution\n2. Substantial fines\n3. Asset seizure\n4. Potential imprisonment\n\nThe specific legal framework and penalties can vary between jurisdictions, but money laundering is generally treated as a serious criminal activity.",
